<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p><strong>An Undisclosed Location in the Himalayan foothills, February 1, 1950:</strong><br />
<br />
<em>A dozen men dressed in green Army fatigues and just as many children &#8212; most of them orphaned infant girls, many of them deformed or otherwise</em> undesirable &#8212; <em>wait on the edge of a forest in a place few people know of and even fewer speak of as the moon begins to rise. The only lights are the stars and small oil lamps. The men can see their breath in the cool air. Two of the men are speaking.</em><br />
<br />
<br />
&quot;So what will happen to them?&quot;<br />
<br />
<em>The shorter of the two men brings a cigarette up to his scarred mouth.</em> &quot;Whatever it is, it's worth it. Besides, these are orphans. No one will miss them.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Still, you have to wonder, Jūn, what do the <em>Yezu</em> do with them? What could they want with them?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Whatever it is, it's worth it.&quot; <em>The short, scarred man takes a long drag from his cigarette and continues to stare into the bamboo, not looking at his co-worker once.</em><br />
<br />
&quot;How could you be so sure?&quot;<br />
<br />
<em>The man takes the cigarette from his mouth, flicks it onto the ground next to his boot, and stamps it out.</em> &quot;Where are you from, Fāng?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Pardon?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;I said, 'Where are you from?' It's a simple question.&quot;<br />
<br />
<em>The man is taken aback by the question, and the change in his posture shows it.</em> &quot;&#8230;A small village north of Baoshan.&quot;<br />
<br />
<em>The other nods, and reaches for another cigarette. After a second, he offers the taller man one, an offer that is quietly refused.</em> &quot;So you never had to deal with the <em>rìběn guizi,</em> then?&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;They kept bombing us, because the Americans, the Flying Tigers, had been stationed in Baoshan.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Everyone was bombed. Did you ever see the actual Army, face-to-face?&quot; <em>To this, the taller man can only answer in the negative.</em> &quot;Well I'm from Nanking. And I got to see the filthy <em>huang jun</em> a lot. They were the last thing my mother, my brother, and my sister ever saw.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Jūn, I'm sorry &#8212; &quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Sorry? Sorry? You're sorry?! No. You're not sorry. You weren't there. You didn't see what I did. You didn't have to bury anyone after seeing what those &#8212; those <em>dogs</em> had done to them. If you were truly sorry, you'd be just as willing as I am to do anything, <em>anything</em>, to make sure our country is never subject to foreign abuse ever again. That's why it doesn't matter. That's why it's worth it. That's why we're giving these orphans to the Wild Men in exchange for weapons. Because whatever these children are going to experience, it's nothing compared to what our people have already seen, to what they're protecting the future from ever seeing!&quot;<br />
<br />
<em>At this point, the man's near-shouting has stopped, and he is slowly catching his breath. As he does, a small, red light appears in the forest in front of the small group. It's quickly joined by another, and then perhaps a dozen more.</em> &quot;Light's out, lights out!&quot; <em>The other men are quick to concede, as the sound of footsteps in the underbrush becomes audible and slowly grows louder. Jūn, the man from Nanking, steps forward as a singular light begins to approach the treeline in the small clearing.</em> &quot;Stay here, Fāng. And that goes for the rest of you, too!&quot; <em>Quietly, to Fāng, he says,</em> &quot;If I'm not back by sunrise, assume that the deal's gone badly and just head back. Do with the tithes what you will.&quot;<br />
<br />
<em>The man steps off into the brush by himself; slowly, the red lights disappear as the sound of breaking brush recedes into the night. Despite his fears and the fears of his coworkers, the man returns just as the sun begins to rise through the bamboo, accompanied by a lone Engineer. As the Engineer inspects the</em> stock, <em>the man walks over to where his fellow stands, pulls out a cigarette, lights it with shaking hands, and turns to the group.</em> &quot;Leave the offering, the <em>Yezu</em> will take care of the rest!&quot; <em>Quietly, quickly, they leave the forest, not looking back.</em></p>
<hr />
<hr />
<p><br />
<strong>The City of Fallenhold, Year of the Revival 54, Night 11 of the Season of the Warming North:</strong><br />
<br />
<em>Hurts. Always hurts. Still remember the songs. They wanted us to forget the songs. Can't sing, have to learn the songs in other ways. Miss the sound of mother's voice.</em><br />
<br />
<em>No mirrors. Not allowed mirrors. Steal looks at reflection when I can. What looks back isn't me. They don't like it when we think about those things. They take some of us away sometimes, we never see the ones They take away again.</em><br />
<br />
<em>We never sleep but we're never tired. Always standing and walking. Strong legs. But not like father's. Like a cricket. Girls aren't supposed to have legs like a cricket, are they?</em><br />
<br />
<em>Always hungry. They never give us enough to eat. Every meal the same. I don't like the way it tastes. Looks like worms. I think it</em> is <em>worms. Can't chew. Mouth doesn't work the same anymore. When I see my reflection, that always scares me.</em><br />
<br />
<em>They move us around a lot. They don't let us use the big hallways, They want us in the little tunnels. Always crouching. But that's ok. Strong legs. But not like father's.</em><br />
<br />
<em>I remember soldiers. Angry. Pushing and shoving and grabbing and pulling. Very long journey. Soldiers didn't feed us either. They left some of us behind. Hope the ones that were left are ok now.</em><br />
<br />
<em>Sometimes there's no memory. But it's not like sleeping. They take us somewhere or tell us to go somewhere and there's bright light and then nothing and then we're back and we know new things but we weren't taught. Then They make us use what we know. We talk to their machines but their machines don't know songs. Not very fun to talk to.</em><br />
<br />
<em>Sometimes the machines talk back, though. They don't tell us anything fun like secrets or stories or songs. They don't use real words but we understand and sometimes there's a problem and we fix it. Sometimes we don't understand the problem so we show Them. Sometimes we don't work on talking machines. Some of us still have hands and They make them work on the pipes and other things.</em><br />
<br />
<em>I miss hands. They took my hands. They gave me blades. Like a mantis. I can fix some of Their machines now, can feel little problems and tell Their talking machines where the little problems are.</em><br />
<br />
<em>Sometimes there's more of us. Sometimes the new ones talk about a War. The new ones are always scared. They usually have new songs, though. I wish mother could sing their new songs. Miss the sound of mother's voice.</em><br />
<br />
<em>We're in a new place. They made us ride in a strange train for a very long time. Many of us in a small space. No sitting for a long time. That's ok, though. Strong legs. But not like father's. Like a cricket.</em><br />
<br />
<em>New knowledge without learning. Strange knowledge. Weird machines. Machines that attach to people. Don't like this new knowledge. Don't want to use it.</em><br />
<br />
<em>They brought children to us. Scared. Dirty. Lots of children. I haven't seen this many children in one place for a long time. Singing would help, but can't sing. Try to talk to the children but they can't hear me.</em><br />
<br />
<em>Have to help Them put weird machines on the children. I don't like this. I can't stop They're making me do it I'm sorry I'm sorry I'm sorry I'm sorry I'm sorry I'm sorry I'm sorry no please why are you making me do this they're just children please stop I'm so sorry.</em><br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<em>I tried to stop Them. They're taking me away now. The others didn't even stop to watch. Except one. They're with me now. They're taking both of us. I try to sing, but I can't. But I tell the other the songs I know. Miss the sound of mother's voice.</em><br /></p>
</div>
